**Comparative Text Classification with Logistic Regression, RNN, LSTM, and GRU**

Group 18 \- Formative 2

**Abstract**  
This report evaluates text classification pipelines spanning traditional machine learning model Logistic Regression, recurrent neural networks (RNNs), gated recurrent units (GRUs), and long short-term memory (LSTM). The study focuses on how representation choices (CountVectorizer/TF-IDF versus dense, pre-trained embeddings) influence predictive performance on a three-class sentiment classification dataset comprising 5,842 financial news sentences. Results indicate that GRU models combined with domain-aware embeddings (FinBERT features) achieve the highest test accuracy and F1-score. At the same time, TF-IDF and Logistic Regression remain a strong and computationally efficient baseline.

**1\. Introduction**  
Text classification assigns discrete labels to natural-language inputs and underpins applications such as sentiment analysis, intent detection, and topic labeling. In financial and news domains, language is concise, entity-rich, and sensitive to subtle wording, motivating careful comparison of text representations and model families.

**Problem statement:**  
Given a sentence x, predict its sentiment label y in {negative, neutral, positive}. The objective is to develop and compare models that generalize across varied financial phrasing.

**Objectives:**  
(i) Establish competitive baselines with Logistic Regression and sparse features;  
(ii) Evaluate sequence models (RNN, GRU) that exploit word order;  
(iii) Quantify the impact of embedding strategies, including pretrained and domain-adapted embeddings.

**Research questions:**  
Q1: How do sparse-feature baselines compare to RNN/GRU sequence models?  
Q2: Which embeddings yield the largest gains within each model family?  
Q3: What accuracy–complexity trade-offs emerge across pipelines?

**Dataset justification:**  
The dataset contains labeled financial news sentences with three sentiment classes, enabling systematic evaluation of embedding choices under domain-specific vocabulary and subtle sentiment cues. This framing aligns with comparative embedding analysis.

**2\. Literature review**  
Sparse vector-space representations such as bag-of-words and TF-IDF remain strong baselines for text categorization when coupled with linear classifiers due to convex optimization and interpretability \[1\], \[2\]. Distributed word representations, including Word2Vec and GloVe, encode semantic similarity and mitigate sparsity, often improving generalization \[3\], \[4\]. Recurrent neural networks model token sequences but may suffer from vanishing gradients; gated variants such as GRU improve learning stability through update and reset gates \[5\], \[6\]. Contextual encoders such as BERT learn task-relevant representations via self-attention and frequently outperform static embeddings on downstream tasks \[7\]. Domain-adapted variants (e.g., FinBERT) can further improve performance on financial text \[8\].

**3\. Methodology**

**3.1 Dataset**  
The experiments use a labeled dataset of 5,842 financial news sentences with three sentiment classes (negative, neutral, positive).

*Figure1: Data Class Distribution*  
![][image1]

**3.2. Preprocessing**  
Two preprocessing tracks were used to support fair comparison across model families:

1.  Sparse-feature pipeline (Logistic Regression / LinearSVC / Naive Bayes): text normalization, tokenization, and conversion to high-dimensional vectors using CountVectorizer (unigrams) and TF-IDF (unigrams and bigrams). Class-weight balancing was applied for linear models to mitigate class imbalance.  
2. Sequence pipeline (RNN/GRU): Keras tokenization to integer sequences, padding/truncation to a fixed sequence length, and embedding lookup using either pretrained embeddings (e.g., GloVe), domain embeddings/features (FinBERT), or synthetic baselines (random or averaged TF-IDF-derived embeddings).

**3.3 Models and Embeddings (Logistic Regression, RNN, GRU, and LSTM)**  
**Logistic Regression.** Logistic Regression was selected as a strong baseline for text classification because it performs well with sparse TF-IDF features, is efficient to train, and offers interpretable weights indicating influential terms. The classifier estimates class probabilities through a softmax over linear decision functions.

**RNN.** A bidirectional RNN was evaluated to capture sequence information from both left-to-right and right-to-left contexts. Embedding strategies included TF-IDF projections and pretrained word vectors (Word2Vec CBOW/Skip-gram, GloVe).

**GRU.** GRU models were used to improve recurrent learning stability through gating mechanisms and to better capture dependencies in sentences. The main architecture uses an embedding layer followed by two GRU layers (64 units each) and a 3-class softmax output layer. Embedding sources included GloVe, Word2Vec, FastText, TF-IDF averaged embeddings, random embeddings, and FinBERT feature vectors.

**5\. Discussions**  
The experiments highlight three consistent patterns. First, TF-IDF with Logistic Regression provides a strong and efficient baseline, achieving the best Logistic Regression accuracy (0.663) in the submitted variants. Second, sequence models benefit from pretrained embeddings; for the bidirectional RNN, GloVe outperformed Word2Vec configurations. Third, GRU models achieved the highest overall accuracy and F1-score when paired with FinBERT features (0.721 accuracy, 0.723 F1), indicating that domain-adapted representations can be more impactful than architecture changes alone.

Log-loss results (where available) suggest that some linear models provide better-calibrated probability estimates than certain deep configurations, even when accuracy is comparable. This is relevant for downstream decision-making where probability reliability matters.

**5.1 Limitations**  
**Several limitations apply:**   
(i) The results aggregate across a limited set of hyperparameters; deeper tuning (dropout, sequence length, learning-rate schedules) may improve RNN/GRU performance.  
(ii) Not all models report log loss (e.g., LinearSVC), limiting calibration comparison.   
(iii) Domain embeddings were used as fixed feature extractors; end-to-end fine-tuning of contextual transformers was not evaluated.

**6\. Conclusion and Future Work**  
This report compared sparse-feature baselines, bidirectional RNNs, and GRUs under multiple embedding strategies on a three-class financial sentiment dataset. GRU with FinBERT features achieved the strongest overall performance, while TF-IDF \+ Logistic Regression remained a competitive, lightweight baseline. The findings support prioritizing representation quality (pretrained and domain-adapted embeddings) alongside model selection.  
**Future work.** Potential extensions include (i) fine-tuning transformer encoders (e.g., BERT/FinBERT) end-to-end, (ii) systematic calibration analysis (ECE, reliability diagrams), (iii) confusion-matrix driven error analysis by class, and (iv) expanded hyperparameter searches for recurrent models.
